abstract: A court majority ruled that juries were not given sufficient say over which inmates should be put to death.
snippet: A court majority ruled that juries were not given sufficient say over which inmates should be put to death.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court struck down an aspect of Florida’s capital punishment system on Tuesday, saying it did not give jurors a sufficient role in deciding whether defendants should be put to death.

abstract: The Energy Department and the Pentagon have been readying a weapon with a build-it-smaller approach, setting off a philosophical clash in the world of nuclear arms.
snippet: The Energy Department and the Pentagon have been readying a weapon with a build-it-smaller approach, setting off a philosophical clash in the world of nuclear arms.
lead_paragraph: As North Korea dug tunnels at its nuclear test site last fall, watched by American spy satellites, the Obama administration was preparing a test of its own in the Nevada desert.

abstract: Not all of the super-rich are smug and selfish.
snippet: Not all of the super-rich are smug and selfish.
lead_paragraph: Re “Privilege, pathology and power” (Jan. 2-3): Paul Krugman implicates all billionaires as smug, selfish, pathological and Republican. Hence they are without empathy, out of touch, and use their money and power to influence elections. What about George Soros, Eli Broad, David Geffen and Tom Steyer? Are they without gobs of money, ego or the desire to inject their own “statist” principles into elections? Have they not sworn to spend countless millions in an effort to “re-shape” America? Mr. Krugman would do better to write about both sides of the billionaires’ battle.

abstract: Every year, amid the carnival of firings on the Monday after the N.F.L.’s regular-season finale, the team owners often escape responsibility for failure.
snippet: Every year, amid the carnival of firings on the Monday after the N.F.L.’s regular-season finale, the team owners often escape responsibility for failure.
lead_paragraph: In September, after watching the Giants beat Washington to earn their first win in what was to be Tom Coughlin’s final season, I cautioned disgruntled fans.

abstract: The gossips say that a woman’s boyfriend is gay. Should her sister pass on those tales?
snippet: The gossips say that a woman’s boyfriend is gay. Should her sister pass on those tales?
lead_paragraph: My sister has been dating her boyfriend for two years. They live together and seem mostly happy. And I am happy for them, except for one thing: I am about 99 percent sure he is gay. Now, I have no problem with homosexuality, but you can understand my concern. Also, I am not the only one who thinks this. Several male friends have told me that he has tried to kiss other men or grab their crotches. I would like to bring this up with my sister. How should I do it?

headline_main: So You Think Your Sister’s Boyfriend Is Gay

abstract: The death of Alan Kurdi, 2, which focused the world on refugees, was just one chapter of a sprawling family’s story in its desperate attempts to escape Syria and find a new home.
snippet: The death of Alan Kurdi, 2, which focused the world on refugees, was just one chapter of a sprawling family’s story in its desperate attempts to escape Syria and find a new home.
lead_paragraph: ISTANBUL — Friday is the first anniversary of the death of Alan Kurdi, a 2-year-old Syrian refugee whose drowned body was discovered on a beach in Turkey. Photos of the boy shocked the world and put a human face on the refugee crisis. Since then hundreds of children have died in the fighting in Syria and on the refugee trail. Anne Barnard, The Times’ Beirut Bureau chief who leads our coverage in Syria, reported on Alan’s death and his sprawling family’s attempts to escape worn-torn Syria. This article originally ran on Dec. 27, 2015.

abstract: Thirty years ago Americans were even unsure how to say Hyundai’s name, but the carmaker’s latest entry in the crossover class is worthy of attention.
snippet: Thirty years ago Americans were even unsure how to say Hyundai’s name, but the carmaker’s latest entry in the crossover class is worthy of attention.
lead_paragraph: WHEN Hyundai arrived in the United States some 30 years ago, Americans had to learn the pronunciation (rhymes with Sunday). Its first car stateside, the Excel, rode on borrowed Mitsubishi mechanicals. Car and Driver’s assessment? “The Excel won’t make your heart soar.”
headline_main: Video Review: Hyundai’s Tucson Holds Its Own in a Class of Heavy Hitters
headline_print_headline: Tucson Holds Its Own in a Tough Class

abstract: The prosecutor is releasing material favorable to the officers involved in the Cleveland boy’s death, and the family fears there is an effort to avoid indictments.
snippet: The prosecutor is releasing material favorable to the officers involved in the Cleveland boy’s death, and the family fears there is an effort to avoid indictments.
lead_paragraph: The Cleveland grand jury has been conducting its work in private, investigating the police shooting of a 12-year-old boy named Tamir Rice that set off protests nationwide. But a steady stream of evidence has been trickling out to the public.

snippet: Hospitality and Gambling Interests Delay Closing of Tax Loophole | Frank Quattrone’s Comeback
lead_paragraph: REGULATIONS CREATE OBSTACLES FOR RAILWAY MERGERS | In the mid-1990s, a wave of mergers was blamed for lost cargo, crashes, derailments, death and billions of lost dollars. The move to consolidate had shrunk the number of major railroad operators in North America to seven from 56 and new rules came in 2001 making potential acquisitions harder. Now, those rules are being tested,Leslie Picker reports in DealBook.
